    <strong>dramatically more comparisons and swaps</strong> than Merge Sort or Quick Sort as array size grows.
    For n=1000, bubble sort needs ~500,000 operations vs ~10,000 for O(n log n) algorithms — a
    <strong>50× difference</strong>. Bubble sort is only acceptable for tiny arrays (&lt;20 elements)
    or nearly-sorted data. Real-world libraries (Python's Timsort, Java's Arrays.sort) use
    O(n log n) algorithms for good reason.
