    .limitation-card { animation-delay: 0.1s; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>📧 Real-Time Email Validation</h1>

  <!-- ── Validator Card ── -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2>🔍 Live Validator</h2>

    <div class="input-wrapper">
      <span class="email-icon">✉️</span>
      <input
        id="emailInput"
        type="text"
        placeholder="Enter an email address…"
        autocomplete="off"
        spellcheck="false"
        aria-label="Email address input"
        aria-describedby="statusMsg"
      />
      <span class="status-icon" id="statusIcon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    </div>

    <div id="statusMsg" class="neutral" role="status" aria-live="polite">
      Start typing to validate…
    </div>

    <div class="stats-row">
      <div class="stat-chip">
        <div class="label">Characters</div>
        <div class="value" id="statChars">0</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-chip">
        <div class="label">Local Part</div>
        <div class="value" id="statLocal">—</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-chip">
        <div class="label">Domain</div>
        <div class="value" id="statDomain">—</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-chip">
        <div class="label">TLD</div>
        <div class="value" id="statTld">—</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="regex-box">
      <p>Regex Pattern in Use</p>
      <code id="regexDisplay">/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]{2,}$/</code>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Limitations Card ── -->
  <div class="limitation-card">
    <h2>⚠️ Why Regex Can't Fully Validate Emails</h2>
    <p class="subtitle">
      RFC 5321 &amp; RFC 5322 define email address syntax with far more complexity than
      any practical regex can handle. Here's what most regex patterns get wrong:
    </p>

    <!-- Known Regex Failures -->
    <ul class="issue-list">
      <li>
        <span class="icon">📦</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Quoted strings in local parts</strong><br/>
          <span>RFC 5321 allows <code>"john..doe"@example.com</code> — double dots
          inside quotes are valid, but most regex patterns reject them.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="icon">🌍</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Internationalized domain names (IDN)</strong><br/>
          <span>Addresses like <code>user@münchen.de</code> or <code>用户@例子.广告</code>
          are valid per RFC 6531 but break standard ASCII-only regex.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="icon">🔗</span>
        <div>
          <strong>IP address literals</strong><br/>
          <span><code>user@[192.168.1.1]</code> and <code>user@[IPv6:::1]</code>
          are valid RFC formats almost never handled by regex.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="icon">🏷️</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Comments inside addresses</strong><br/>
          <span>RFC 5322 technically permits <code>(comment)user@example.com</code>
          — legal syntax that regex cannot meaningfully validate.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="icon">📏</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Length constraints are complex</strong><br/>
          <span>Local parts ≤ 64 chars, full address ≤ 254 chars, each domain
          label ≤ 63 chars — most regex patterns ignore all of these.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="icon">🌐</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Single-label domains &amp; new TLDs</strong><br/>
          <span>Intranet addresses like <code>user@localhost</code> are valid in
          private networks. New TLDs like <code>.photography</code> keep expanding.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="icon">🚫</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Regex can't verify deliverability</strong><br/>
          <span>Even a perfectly formatted address like <code>nobody@valid-domain.com</code>
          may bounce — only an SMTP handshake can confirm a mailbox exists.</span>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <!-- RFC-valid edge cases -->
    <div class="examples-label">🧪 Click any example to test it in the validator above</div>
    <div class="examples-grid">
      <div class="example-chip rfc-valid"   data-email='"john..doe"@example.com'>
        <span class="badge">RFC✓</span>"john..doe"@example.com
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-valid"   data-email="user+tag@sub.domain.io">
        <span class="badge">RFC✓</span>user+tag@sub.domain.io
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-valid"   data-email="user@[192.168.1.1]">
        <span class="badge">RFC✓</span>user@[192.168.1.1]
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-valid"   data-email="user@localhost">
        <span class="badge">RFC✓</span>user@localhost
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-invalid" data-email="plainaddress">
        <span class="badge">FAIL</span>plainaddress
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-invalid" data-email="@no-local.com">
        <span class="badge">FAIL</span>@no-local.com
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-invalid" data-email="two@@signs.com">
        <span class="badge">FAIL</span>two@@signs.com
      </div>
      <div class="example-chip rfc-invalid" data-email="spaces in@email.com">
        <span class="badge">FAIL</span>spaces in@email.com
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Production Alternatives -->
    <div class="alt-title">✅ Better Alternatives for Production</div>
    <div class="alternatives">
      <div class="alt-item">
        <strong>1. Minimal Regex + Server-Side Confirmation</strong>
        <p>Use a simple regex only to catch obvious typos on the client side. Always
           send a confirmation email — it's the only reliable proof the address works
           and the user controls it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="alt-item">
        <strong>2. HTML5 Native Validation  <code>type="email"</code></strong>
        <p>The browser's built-in email input type uses a well-tested, spec-aligned
           algorithm (WHATWG Living Standard) that handles most real-world cases
           without any JavaScript.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="alt-item">
        <strong>3. Dedicated Validation Libraries</strong>
        <p>Libraries like <code>email-validator</code> (npm), <code>validator.js</code>,
           or Python's <code>email-validator</code> package implement RFC-aware parsing
           with proper length checks, IDN support, and MX record lookup.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="alt-item">
        <strong>4. DNS / MX Record Lookup (Server-Side)</strong>
        <p>Query the domain's MX records to confirm the domain is configured to
           receive mail. Catches disposable-email domains and typos like
           <code>@gmial.com</code> before they enter your database.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="alt-item">
        <strong>5. Email Verification APIs</strong>
        <p>Services like ZeroBounce, Hunter.io, or Abstract API perform syntax checks,
           MX lookup, SMTP probing, and disposable-address detection in a single call —
           ideal for high-value sign-up flows.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <footer>
    RFC references:
    <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5321" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RFC 5321</a> ·
    <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5322" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RFC 5322</a> ·
    <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6531" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RFC 6531</a>
  </footer>

  <script>
    // ── Config ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // A pragmatic regex: good enough for UX feedback, not RFC-complete.
    // Requires: non-whitespace/@ chars · @ · domain · dot · 2+ char TLD
    const EMAIL_REGEX = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]{2,}$/;

    // ── DOM Refs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    const input      = document.getElementById('emailInput');
    const statusMsg  = document.getElementById('statusMsg');
    const statusIcon = document.getElementById('statusIcon');
    const statChars  = document.getElementById('statChars');
    const statLocal  = document.getElementById('statLocal');
    const statDomain = document.getElementById('statDomain');
    const statTld    = document.getElementById('statTld');

    // ── Validation Logic ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    function validateEmail(value) {
      const trimmed = value.trim();

      // Reset to neutral when empty
      if (trimmed === '') {
        setNeutral();
        updateStats(trimmed);
        return;
      }

      const isValid = EMAIL_REGEX.test(trimmed);
      isValid ? setValid(trimmed) : setInvalid(trimmed);
      updateStats(trimmed);
    }

    function setValid(value) {
      input.className = 'valid';
      statusMsg.className = 'valid';
      statusMsg.textContent = '✔ Looks like a valid email format.';
      statusIcon.textContent = '✅';
    }

    function setInvalid(value) {
      input.className = 'invalid';
      statusMsg.className = 'invalid';
      statusMsg.textContent = getHint(value);
      statusIcon.textContent = '❌';
    }

    function setNeutral() {
      input.className = '';
      statusMsg.className = 'neutral';
      statusMsg.textContent = 'Start typing to validate…';
      statusIcon.textContent = '';
    }

    // ── Friendly Hints ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    function getHint(value) {
      if (!value.includes('@'))        return '✖ Missing @ symbol.';
      if (value.indexOf('@') === 0)    return '✖ Local part (before @) is empty.';
      if ((value.match(/@/g) || []).length > 1) return '✖ Multiple @ symbols found.';

      const [local, ...rest] = value.split('@');
      const domain = rest.join('@');

      if (!domain)                     return '✖ Missing domain after @.';
      if (!domain.includes('.'))       return '✖ Domain needs at least one dot.';
      if (domain.startsWith('.'))      return '✖ Domain cannot start with a dot.';
      if (domain.endsWith('.'))        return '✖ Domain cannot end with a dot.';
      if (/\s/.test(value))            return '✖ Spaces are not allowed.';

      const tld = domain.split('.').pop();
      if (tld.length < 2)              return '✖ TLD must be at least 2 characters.';

      return '✖ Invalid email format.';
    }

    // ── Stats Panel ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    function updateStats(value) {
      statChars.textContent = value.length;

      if (!value.includes('@')) {
        statLocal.textContent  = '—';
        statDomain.textContent = '—';
        statTld.textContent    = '—';
        return;
      }

      const atIndex = value.indexOf('@');
      const local   = value.slice(0, atIndex);
      const domain  = value.slice(atIndex + 1);
      const parts   = domain.split('.');
      const tld     = parts.length > 1 ? parts[parts.length - 1] : '—';

      statLocal.textContent  = local  || '—';
      statDomain.textContent = domain || '—';
      statTld.textContent    = tld    || '—';
    }

    // ── Event Listeners ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    input.addEventListener('input', () => validateEmail(input.value));
    input.addEventListener('paste', (e) => {
      // Let paste settle before validating
      setTimeout(() => validateEmail(input.value), 0);
    });

    // ── Example Chips ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    document.querySelectorAll('.example-chip').forEach(chip => {
      chip.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const email = chip.dataset.email;
        input.value = email;
        validateEmail(email);
        input.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'center' });
        input.focus();
      });
    });

    // ── Initial Render ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    updateStats('');
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## What's Inside

### 🔧 Validator Features
| Feature | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Real-time feedback** | Validates on every keystroke and paste event |
| **Green border** | Applied via `.valid` class with green glow shadow |
| **Red border** | Applied via `.invalid` class with red glow shadow |
| **Smart hints** | Context-aware error messages (missing `@`, bad TLD, spaces, etc.) |
| **Live stats panel** | Shows character count, local part, domain, and TLD as you type |
| **Regex display** | Shows the exact pattern being used |

### ⚠️ Educational Section Covers
- **7 specific RFC failure cases** with concrete examples
- **Clickable edge-case chips** that load examples directly into the validator so you can see regex pass/fail RFC-valid addresses
- **5 production-ready alternatives** ranging from free (HTML5 `type="email"`) to API-based services

### 🎨 Design Choices
- Fully **self-contained** — zero dependencies, no CDN calls
- **Dark theme** with accessible contrast ratios
- **Responsive** down to mobile widths
- **ARIA live region** on the status message for screen reader support

