    </div>

    <!-- EXPLANATION SECTION -->
    <div class="explanation-section">
        <h3>📚 Why Parameterized Queries Are Safe</h3>
        <div class="explanation-grid">
            <div class="explanation-card danger">
                <h4>💀 The Core Problem</h4>
                <p>SQL injection happens when <strong>code and data are mixed together</strong>. When user input is concatenated directly into a SQL string, the database cannot distinguish between your intended query structure and the attacker's injected commands.</p>
                <br>
                <p>The database parser sees the final string and executes whatever SQL logic it contains — including the attacker's additions.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="explanation-card success">
                <h4>🛡️ The Parameterized Solution</h4>
                <p>Parameterized queries (also called prepared statements) <strong>separate the query structure from the data</strong>. The query template is compiled first, then data is bound to placeholders.</p>
                <br>
                <p>The database knows exactly which parts are "code" (the template) and which are "data" (the parameters). Data can <strong>never</strong> be interpreted as SQL commands.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="explanation-card info">
                <h4>🔬 What Actually Happens</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>The DB compiles the query template once</li>
                    <li>Parameters are sent separately in a different protocol channel</li>
                    <li>Special characters like <code>'</code>, <code>--</code>, <code>;</code> are automatically escaped</li>
                    <li>The query execution plan is fixed and cannot change</li>
                    <li>Even <code>' OR '1'='1</code> becomes just a harmless search string</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="explanation-card warning">
                <h4>⚡ Real-World Impact</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Data theft:</strong> Dump entire databases</li>
                    <li><strong>Authentication bypass:</strong> Login without passwords</li>
                    <li><strong>Data destruction:</strong> DROP TABLE, DELETE records</li>
                    <li><strong>Privilege escalation:</strong> Access admin accounts</li>
                    <li>SQL injection is <strong>#1 in OWASP Top 10</strong> web vulnerabilities</li>
                    <li>Always use parameterized queries or ORMs</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
