<!-- Explanation Section -->
<div class="explanation-section">
    <h2>🔬 Why Parameterized Queries Are Structurally Immune to Injection</h2>

    <div class="explain-grid">
        <div class="explain-card bad">
            <h3>💀 String Concatenation (Vulnerable)</h3>
            <p>The query is built as a single string. User input becomes part of the query's <strong>syntax</strong>.
               The parser cannot distinguish between developer-intended SQL and attacker-injected SQL.</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">// Developer writes:</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> query = <span class="str">"SELECT * FROM products "</span>
  + <span class="str">"WHERE name LIKE '%"</span>
  + <span class="inj">userInput</span>   <span class="cmt">// ← DANGER ZONE</span>
  + <span class="str">"%'"</span>;

<span class="cmt">// User enters:  ' OR '1'='1</span>
<span class="cmt">// Query becomes:</span>
<span class="inj">SELECT * FROM products
WHERE name LIKE '%' OR '1'='1%'</span>
<span class="cmt">// ↑ Always true — returns ALL rows</span>
            </div>

            <p>The database engine receives one string and parses it. By the time it sees the query,
               it has no way to know which parts were written by the developer and which were injected.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="explain-card good">
            <h3>🛡️ Parameterized Query (Safe)</h3>
            <p>The query structure and the data are <strong>sent separately</strong>. The database engine
               compiles the query template first, then binds the value. Syntax is already locked.</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="cmt">// Developer writes:</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> query = <span class="str">"SELECT * FROM products "</span>
  + <span class="str">"WHERE name LIKE ?"</span>;  <span class="cmt">// ← placeholder</span>

<span class="kw">const</span> params = [<span class="param">`%${userInput}%`</span>];
<span class="cmt">// Sent separately to DB engine</span>

<span class="cmt">// User enters:  ' OR '1'='1</span>
<span class="cmt">// DB receives two separate things:</span>
<span class="safe">Query:  "SELECT * FROM products
         WHERE name LIKE ?"</span>
<span class="param">Param:  ["%' OR '1'='1%"]</span>
<span class="cmt">// ↑ Treated as a literal string, not syntax</span>
            </div>

            <p>The query structure is compiled <em>before</em> the value is ever seen. The engine treats
               the parameter as a plain string value — quotes, semicolons, keywords are all inert.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="how-it-works">
        <h3>🧠 The Exact Mechanism — Step by Step</h3>
        <div class="steps">
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <p><strong>Parse phase (parameterized):</strong> The DB engine parses
                   <code style="color:#a5d6ff">SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE ?</code>
                   and builds a query execution plan. The <code style="color:#56d364">?</code> is a
                   typed slot — it expects a string value, not SQL syntax.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <p><strong>Bind phase:</strong> The user's input is bound to that slot as a raw scalar value.
                   The parser is <em>already done</em>. There is no second parse of the user's string.
                   Single quotes in the input are just characters in a string, not SQL delimiters.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <p><strong>Execute phase:</strong> The engine runs the pre-compiled plan with the bound value.
                   <code style="color:#ff6b6b">' OR '1'='1</code> becomes the literal search term — it finds
                   products whose name literally contains that character sequence. Zero rows, no breach.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <p><strong>Why concatenation fails:</strong> With string building, there is only one string
                   by the time the DB sees it. The engine parses it all as SQL. It cannot retroactively
                   know what was "data" vs "code" — that distinction was destroyed when you concatenated.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step">
                <div class="step-num">5</div>
                <p><strong>Escaping is not sufficient:</strong> Manually escaping quotes is fragile — different
                   DB engines have different rules, encoding edge cases exist, and one missed escape is a breach.
                   Parameterization is a <em>structural</em> guarantee, not a sanitization heuristic.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

