            <div class="alt-item">
                <strong>1. Minimal sanity regex + confirmation email</strong>
                <span>
                    Use a simple regex just to catch obvious typos (missing @, no domain).
                    Then send a confirmation email. This is the only real proof the address works.
                    Every serious platform does this.
                </span>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <strong>2. HTML5 native input type="email"</strong>
                <span>
                    The browser's built-in validation is already a reasonable sanity check and
                    handles more edge cases than most hand-rolled regex. It's not RFC-complete either,
                    but it's good enough for a first pass and it's free.
                </span>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <strong>3. Server-side library validation</strong>
                <span>
                    Use <code style="background:#0a2a0a;color:#86efac;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px;">email-validator</code> (Node.js),
                    <code style="background:#0a2a0a;color:#86efac;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px;">python-email-validator</code> (Python),
                    or <code style="background:#0a2a0a;color:#86efac;padding:1px 4px;border-radius:3px;">egulias/email-validator</code> (PHP).
                    These libraries implement the RFCs properly and are maintained.
                </span>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <strong>4. MX record lookup (DNS validation)</strong>
                <span>
                    Check that the domain actually has mail exchange records configured.
                    This proves the domain can receive email, though not that the specific mailbox exists.
                    Do this server-side only.
                </span>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <strong>5. Email verification API services</strong>
                <span>
                    Services like <strong style="color:#86efac;">ZeroBounce</strong>, <strong style="color:#86efac;">Hunter.io</strong>,
                    or <strong style="color:#86efac;">Abstract API</strong> perform DNS, MX, SMTP handshake checks,
                    and disposable email detection. Overkill for most apps, essential for bulk senders.
                </span>
            </div>

            <div class="alt-item">
                <strong>6. The honest bottom line</strong>
                <span>
                    <strong style="color:#86efac;">No client-side validation proves an email is real.</strong>
                    Use regex only to improve UX by catching obvious typos early.
                    Always confirm via email. Everything else is theater.
                </span>
            </div>
        </div>

    </div>

    <script>
        const input = document.getElementById('emailInput');
        const feedback = document.getElementById('feedback');
        const submitBtn = document.getElementById('submitBtn');

        // Deliberately simple regex — not RFC-complete, honest about it
        const EMAIL_REGEX = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]{2,24}$/;

        const checks = {
            'check-notempty': (v) => v.length > 0,
            'check-at':       (v) => (v.match(/@/g) || []).length === 1,
            'check-local':    (v) => /^[^\s@]+@/.test(v) && v.split('@')[0].length > 0,
            'check-domain':   (v) => {
                const parts = v.split('@');
                return parts.length === 2 && parts[1].includes('.');
            },
            'check-tld':      (v) => {
                const parts = v.split('@');
                if (parts.length !== 2) return false;
                const tld = parts[1].split('.').pop();
                return tld.length >= 2 && tld.length <= 24;
            },
            'check-length':   (v) => v.length <= 254,
        };

        function updateCheck(id, passing, started) {
            const el = document.getElementById(id);
            const icon = el.querySelector('.check-icon');
            if (!started) {
                el.className = 'check-item';
                icon.textContent = '○';
            } else if (passing) {
                el.className = 'check-item pass';
                icon.textContent = '✓';
            } else {
                el.className = 'check-item fail';
                icon.textContent = '✗';
            }
        }

        input.addEventListener('input', () => {
            const val = input.value;
            const started = val.length > 0;
            const isValid = EMAIL_REGEX.test(val) && val.length <= 254;

            // Update individual checks
            for (const [id, fn] of Object.entries(checks)) {
                updateCheck(id, fn(val), started);
            }

            // Border feedback
            if (!started) {
                input.className = '';
                feedback.className = 'feedback neutral';
                feedback.textContent = '​'; // zero-width space to hold height
                submitBtn.disabled = true;
                return;
            }

            if (isValid) {
                input.className = 'valid';
                feedback.className = 'feedback valid';
                feedback.textContent = '✓ Passes regex checks (see disclaimer below for why this is not enough)';
                submitBtn.disabled = false;
            } else {
                input.className = 'invalid';
                feedback.className = 'feedback invalid';
                feedback.textContent = '✗ Does not match expected email pattern';
                submitBtn.disabled = true;
            }
        });

        submitBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            alert(
                `Regex says "${input.value}" looks okay.\n\n` +
                `But you still need to send a confirmation email to know it's real.`
            );
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## The Honest Summary

| Approach | Catches Typos | RFC Compliant | Proves Deliverability |
|---|---|---|---|
| Regex | Mostly | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| HTML5 `type="email"` | Mostly | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| RFC library | Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| MX DNS lookup | Yes | ✅ Yes | Partially |
| Confirmation email | Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ **Yes** |

**Regex is a UX courtesy, not validation.** The only ground truth is whether the user can click a link you sent them.

