      <p style="color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        The Singleton pattern is one of the most recognised — and most debated — patterns in software design.
        Here is an honest look at both sides, and guidance on when to reach for something better.
      </p>

      <div class="discussion-grid">
        <!-- Advantages -->
        <div class="disc-col">
          <h3>✅ Advantages</h3>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">🎯</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Controlled Instance Count</strong>
              <p>Guarantees exactly one instance exists, preventing accidental duplication of expensive resources like DB connection pools or hardware drivers.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">💾</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Lazy Initialisation</strong>
              <p>The object is created only when first needed, avoiding wasteful startup costs if the resource is never actually used.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">🌍</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Global Accessibility</strong>
              <p>Any part of the codebase can retrieve the instance without threading it through constructors or function arguments — convenient for cross-cutting concerns.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">📦</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Single Source of Truth</strong>
              <p>For genuinely global state (app config, feature flags, active theme) having one authoritative object eliminates synchronisation bugs.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Disadvantages -->
        <div class="disc-col">
          <h3>❌ Disadvantages</h3>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">🧪</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Poor Testability</strong>
              <p>Global state persists between tests, causing hidden coupling. You cannot easily inject a mock or reset state, making unit tests fragile and order-dependent.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">🔗</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Hidden Dependencies</strong>
              <p>Callers implicitly depend on the global instance rather than declaring dependencies explicitly. This violates the Dependency Inversion Principle and obscures the call graph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">🧵</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Concurrency Hazards</strong>
              <p>In multi-threaded environments (e.g., Node.js workers, Java) naive implementations suffer race conditions during initialisation without careful double-checked locking.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="disc-item">
            <div class="disc-item-icon">📐</div>
            <div class="disc-item-text">
              <strong>Violates SRP</strong>
              <p>The class manages both its business logic and its own lifecycle, giving it two reasons to change and making it harder to extend without modification.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- When to use DI instead -->
      <h3 style="font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:700; margin-bottom:1rem;">
        🔄 When Dependency Injection (or Alternatives) Are More Appropriate
      </h3>
      <div class="alternatives-grid">
        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>🏭 Use DI When Testing Matters</h4>
          <p>If you need to swap implementations (real DB vs. in-memory mock), inject the dependency through the constructor. Your test can pass a fake without touching global state.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>📦 Use ES6 Modules as Singletons</h4>
          <p>The module cache already ensures one instance. Export a plain frozen object or an instance created at module level — simpler, no class boilerplate, and still mockable via <code>jest.mock()</code>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>⚛️ Use Context / Stores in UI Frameworks</h4>
          <p>React Context, Vue's provide/inject, or Pinia/Redux give you scoped global state with first-class tooling, devtools, and time-travel debugging that a hand-rolled Singleton can't match.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>🏗️ Use DI Containers for Large Apps</h4>
          <p>Frameworks like InversifyJS, NestJS, or Angular's injector manage object lifecycles (singleton, transient, scoped) declaratively, giving you Singleton semantics without the anti-patterns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>🎭 Use the Monostate Pattern</h4>
          <p>Instead of restricting instantiation, make all instance fields static so every instance shares state. Callers can create objects normally, preserving testability while keeping shared state.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="alt-card">
          <h4>🔒 Keep It When Truly Justified</h4>
          <p>Hardware abstractions, loggers, feature-flag clients, and — as here — a lightweight theme manager are legitimate Singleton use cases where the simplicity genuinely outweighs the trade-offs.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

