  <section class="section reveal" id="tradeoffs">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-icon">⚖️</div>
      <h2>Honest Trade-off Analysis</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="pros-cons-grid">
      <!-- PROS -->
      <div class="card pros-card">
        <h3>✅ Genuine Strengths</h3>
        <ul class="check-list">
          <li>
            <span class="icon">✔️</span>
            <span><strong>Single source of truth.</strong>
            No possibility of two managers disagreeing about the current theme.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">✔️</span>
            <span><strong>Lazy initialisation.</strong>
            The instance is created only when first needed, not at import time.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">✔️</span>
            <span><strong>Controlled access.</strong>
            The private constructor prevents accidental instantiation.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">✔️</span>
            <span><strong>Appropriate for true globals.</strong>
            A theme, a logger, a hardware driver — things that genuinely
            exist once in the real world.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">✔️</span>
            <span><strong>Easy cross-component coordination.</strong>
            Any module can call <code>getInstance()</code> without
            prop-drilling or context providers.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- CONS -->
      <div class="card cons-card">
        <h3>❌ Real Pitfalls</h3>
        <ul class="check-list">
          <li>
            <span class="icon">⚠️</span>
            <span><strong>Hidden global state.</strong>
            Functions that call <code>getInstance()</code> internally are
            secretly coupled to global state — hard to reason about.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">⚠️</span>
            <span><strong>Testing nightmare.</strong>
            State persists between tests. You must manually reset or
            hack the private field between each test run.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">⚠️</span>
            <span><strong>Tight coupling.</strong>
            Consumers depend on the concrete class, not an interface.
            Swapping implementations requires changing every call site.</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="icon">⚠️</span>
            <span><strong>Concurrency issues.</strong>
