<section class="explanation">

  <!-- 1. How the algorithm works -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2><span class="icon">🔍</span> How the Recursive Algorithm Works</h2>
    <p>
      Each call to <code>drawBranch(x, y, length, angle, depth)</code> does three things:
    </p>
    <ol style="margin-top:8px;">
      <li><strong>Draw</strong> a line segment from <em>(x, y)</em> in the given direction.</li>
      <li><strong>Recurse left</strong> – rotate by −25 ° and reduce length by 30 %.</li>
      <li><strong>Recurse right</strong> – rotate by +25 ° and reduce length by 30 %.</li>
    </ol>
    <p style="margin-top:8px;">
      The base case is <code>depth === 0</code>, at which point the function returns
      immediately without drawing. This guarantees the recursion always terminates.
    </p>
    <pre><code><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(x, y, len, angle, depth) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (depth === <span class="num">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span>;          <span class="cm">// base case – stop recursing</span>

  <span class="kw">const</span> x2 = x + Math.<span class="fn">cos</span>(angle) * len;
  <span class="kw">const</span> y2 = y + Math.<span class="fn">sin</span>(angle) * len;

  ctx.<span class="fn">beginPath</span>();
  ctx.<span class="fn">moveTo</span>(x,  y);
  ctx.<span class="fn">lineTo</span>(x2, y2);
  ctx.<span class="fn">stroke</span>();

  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(x2, y2, len * <span class="num">0.7</span>, angle - <span class="num">0.436</span>, depth - <span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// left</span>
  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(x2, y2, len * <span class="num">0.7</span>, angle + <span class="num">0.436</span>, depth - <span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// right</span>
}</code></pre>

    <!-- colour legend -->
    <p style="margin-top:12px;">Branch colour shifts from brown (trunk) to green (leaves):</p>
    <div class="legend" id="legend"></div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2. Recursion depth limits -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2><span class="icon">📐</span> Understanding Recursion Depth Limits</h2>
    <p>
      At depth <em>d</em> a binary-branching tree produces
      <strong>2<sup>d+1</sup> − 1</strong> total branches.
      The table below shows how quickly this grows:
    </p>
    <pre><code>Depth │ Branches │ Max simultaneous stack frames
──────┼──────────┼──────────────────────────────
  1   │        1 │   2
  4   │       31 │   5
  7   │      255 │   8
 10   │    2 047 │  11
 12   │    8 191 │  13
 20   │1 048 575 │  21   ← never do this recursively!</code></pre>
    <p style="margin-top:8px;">
      Notice that the <em>branch count</em> grows exponentially, but the
      <em>maximum stack depth</em> only grows linearly — it equals
      <code>depth + 1</code>. This is because the two recursive calls are
      <strong>sequential, not simultaneous</strong>: the left subtree is fully
      explored before the right one begins, so only one path from root to leaf
      is on the call stack at any moment.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- 3. Stack overflow risks -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2><span class="icon">💥</span> Stack Overflow Risks</h2>
    <p>
      Every function call in JavaScript (and most languages) pushes a
      <strong>stack frame</strong> onto the call stack. A stack frame stores:
    </p>
    <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
      <li>The function's local variables (<code>x</code>, <code>y</code>, <code>len</code>, …)</li>
      <li>The return address — where execution resumes after the call</li>
      <li>Internal bookkeeping used by the JavaScript engine</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin-top:8px;">
      Browser engines typically allow between <strong>10 000 and 15 000</strong>
      nested frames before throwing a
      <code style="color:#ff7b72;">RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</code>.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-top:8px;">
      For our tree the maximum simultaneous depth is only <code>depth + 1</code>
      (≤ 13 here), so there is <em>no real risk</em> in this demo.
      However, if you accidentally removed the base case, or if the branching
      factor were larger (e.g. a ternary tree at depth 20), you would hit the
      limit quickly.
    </p>
    <p style="margin-top:8px;">
      <strong>Common causes of accidental stack overflow:</strong>
    </p>
    <ul style="margin-top:6px;">
      <li>Missing or unreachable base case</li>
      <li>Recursive calls on data structures with cycles (graphs without a
          visited set)</li>
      <li>Mutual recursion (<code>A</code> calls <code>B</code> calls <code>A</code> …)
          with no termination</li>
      <li>Very deep trees / linked lists processed node-by-node</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- 4. Practical solutions -->
  <div class="card">
    <h2><span class="icon">🛠️</span> Practical Solutions</h2>

    <p><strong>1 — Iterative conversion with an explicit stack</strong></p>
    <p style="margin-top:4px;">
      Any recursive algorithm can be rewritten using a manual stack (an array)
      and a loop. The idea is to simulate what the call stack does automatically,
      but in heap memory — which is orders of magnitude larger.
    </p>
    <pre><code><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawTreeIterative</span>(x0, y0, len0, angle0, maxDepth) {
  <span class="cm">// Each item on our manual stack mirrors a recursive call's arguments</span>
  <span class="kw">const</span> stack = [{ x: x0, y: y0, len: len0, angle: angle0, depth: maxDepth }];

  <span class="kw">while</span> (stack.length > <span class="num">0</span>) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> { x, y, len, angle, depth } = stack.<span class="fn">pop</span>();
    <span class="kw">if</span> (depth === <span class="num">0</span>) <span class="kw">continue</span>;

    <span class="kw">const</span> x2 = x + Math.<span class="fn">cos</span>(angle) * len;
    <span class="kw">const</span> y2 = y + Math.<span class="fn">sin</span>(angle) * len;
    ctx.<span class="fn">beginPath</span>(); ctx.<span class="fn">moveTo</span>(x, y); ctx.<span class="fn">lineTo</span>(x2, y2); ctx.<span class="fn">stroke</span>();

    <span class="cm">// Push children — order reversed so left is processed first</span>
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, len: len*<span class="num">0.7</span>, angle: angle+<span class="num">0.436</span>, depth: depth-<span class="num">1</span> });
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>({ x: x2, y: y2, len: len*<span class="num">0.7</span>, angle: angle-<span class="num">0.436</span>, depth: depth-<span class="num">1</span> });
  }
}</code></pre>
    <p style="margin-top:10px;">
      This version can safely handle depths of 50, 100, or more — the only
      limit is available heap memory, not the call stack.
    </p>

    <p style="margin-top:14px;"><strong>2 — Tail-call optimisation (TCO)</strong></p>
    <p style="margin-top:4px;">
      When a recursive call is the <em>very last</em> operation in a function,
      some engines can reuse the current stack frame instead of pushing a new
      one. This is called <em>tail-call optimisation</em>. Unfortunately, our
      tree function is <strong>not</strong> tail-recursive because it makes
      <em>two</em> recursive calls and must return from the first before making
      the second. TCO also has limited browser support (only Safari as of 2024).
    </p>

    <p style="margin-top:14px;"><strong>3 — Trampolining</strong></p>
    <p style="margin-top:4px;">
      A trampoline is a loop that repeatedly calls a function that returns
      either a result or a <em>thunk</em> (a zero-argument function representing
      the next step). This converts deep recursion into a flat loop without
      rewriting the entire algorithm.
    </p>
    <pre><code><span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span> = fn => (...args) => {
  <span class="kw">let</span> result = fn(...args);
  <span class="kw">while</span> (<span class="kw">typeof</span> result === <span class="str">'function'</span>) result = result();
  <span class="kw">return</span> result;
};</code></pre>

    <p style="margin-top:14px;"><strong>4 — Increase the stack size (server-side)</strong></p>
    <p style="margin-top:4px;">
      In Node.js you can launch the process with
      <code>node --stack-size=65536 app.js</code> to enlarge the call stack.
      This is sometimes appropriate for deeply recursive data-processing scripts
      but is <strong>not available in browsers</strong>.
    </p>

    <p style="margin-top:14px;"><strong>5 — Memoisation / dynamic programming</strong></p>
    <p style="margin-top:4px;">
      When recursive calls repeat the same sub-problems (e.g. Fibonacci,
      shortest paths), caching results in a map eliminates redundant calls and
      often dramatically reduces depth as well as time complexity.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- 5. Summary table -->
  <div class="card">
