<div class="explanation">

  <div class="exp-card why">
    <h2>🐛 Why the Buggy Version Fails</h2>
    <p>
      Each button click fires a <code>setTimeout</code> callback that performs a
      classic <strong>read → modify → write</strong> sequence on the shared
      <code>buggyCount</code> variable. Because <code>setTimeout</code> is
      asynchronous, <em>multiple callbacks can be in-flight simultaneously</em>.
      Every callback <strong>captures the same stale value</strong> at the moment
      it reads <code>buggyCount</code>, computes a new value, then overwrites the
      variable — silently discarding every other concurrent write.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Click +1 five times quickly → each callback reads <code>0</code></li>
      <li>All five callbacks write <code>1</code> back → final count is <code>1</code>, not <code>5</code></li>
      <li>The displayed number <strong>falls behind</strong> or jumps unpredictably</li>
      <li>Lost updates are invisible — no error is thrown</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="exp-card flow">
    <h2>🔬 Timeline of a Race Condition (3 rapid clicks, delay = 200 ms)</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">t = 0 ms</span>  <span class="tl-dot blue"></span>  Click 1 fires — reads count = <strong>0</strong>, schedules write of 1</div>
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">t = 50 ms</span> <span class="tl-dot blue"></span>  Click 2 fires — reads count = <strong>0</strong> (still!), schedules write of 1</div>
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">t = 90 ms</span> <span class="tl-dot blue"></span>  Click 3 fires — reads count = <strong>0</strong> (still!), schedules write of 1</div>
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">t = 200 ms</span><span class="tl-dot warn"></span> Callback 1 resolves → writes count = <strong>1</strong> ✓</div>
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">t = 250 ms</span><span class="tl-dot red"></span>  Callback 2 resolves → writes count = <strong>1</strong> ✗ (overwrites!)</div>
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">t = 290 ms</span><span class="tl-dot red"></span>  Callback 3 resolves → writes count = <strong>1</strong> ✗ (overwrites!)</div>
      <div class="tl-row"><span class="tl-time">Final</span>     <span class="tl-dot red"></span>  Expected <strong>3</strong>, got <strong>1</strong> — two updates lost!</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="exp-card how">
    <h2>✅ How the Fix Works</h2>
    <p>
      The fixed version uses a <strong>pending-delta queue</strong> pattern.
      Instead of reading and writing the shared variable inside the async
      callback, each click <em>immediately</em> accumulates its delta into a
      separate <code>fixedPending</code> counter (a synchronous operation — no
      race possible). A single scheduled callback then drains the entire pending
      queue in one atomic step:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>fixedPending</code> is incremented synchronously on every click</li>
      <li>Only <strong>one</strong> <code>setTimeout</code> is ever in-flight at a time (guard flag)</li>
      <li>When it fires it reads <code>fixedPending</code> — which already holds <em>all</em> accumulated deltas — adds it to <code>fixedCount</code>, then resets the queue</li>
      <li>No stale reads, no lost writes — every click is counted exactly once</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

