          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Click #1</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code>, schedules
            <code>setTimeout(fn, 50)</code>. The callback has captured
            <span class="bad">count = 0</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=10ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-blue"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-blue"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Click #2</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code> (still 0!),
            schedules another callback. It also captured <span class="bad">count = 0</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=20ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-blue"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-blue"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Click #3</strong> — reads <code>count = 0</code> again.
            Third callback captures <span class="bad">count = 0</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=50ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-orange"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-orange"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Callback #1 fires</strong> — computes <code>0 + 1 = 1</code>,
            writes <code>count = 1</code>. ✓ Correct so far.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=60ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-orange"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert line-orange"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Callback #2 fires</strong> — computes <span class="bad">0 + 1 = 1</span>,
            writes <code>count = 1</code>. ✗ Overwrites the correct value!
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-time">t=70ms</div>
          <div class="tl-line-wrap">
            <div class="tl-dot dot-red"></div>
            <div class="tl-vert" style="background:transparent"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tl-content">
            <strong>Callback #3 fires</strong> — computes <span class="bad">0 + 1 = 1</span>,
            writes <code>count = 1</code>. ✗ Three clicks, but count shows
            <span class="bad">1</span> instead of <span class="good">3</span>.
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Code Comparison -->
    <div class="exp-card">
      <h3><span class="badge badge-info">💻 Code</span> Buggy vs Fixed — Side by Side</h3>

      <div class="code-compare">

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header code-header-bug">🐛 Buggy — stale closure capture</div>
          <pre><span class="hl-comment">// Shared mutable state</span>
<span class="hl-keyword">let</span> <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-number">0</span>;

button.<span class="hl-fn">addEventListener</span>(<span class="hl-string">'click'</span>, () => {
  <span class="hl-comment">// ❌ Read happens NOW (sync)</span>
  <span class="hl-keyword">const</span> <span class="hl-bad">snapshot</span> = <span class="hl-var">count</span>;

  <span class="hl-fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
    <span class="hl-comment">// ❌ Write uses stale snapshot</span>
    <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-bad">snapshot</span> + <span class="hl-number">1</span>;
    display.<span class="hl-var">textContent</span> = <span class="hl-var">count</span>;
  }, <span class="hl-number">50</span>);
});</pre>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header code-header-fix">✅ Fixed — read inside the callback</div>
          <pre><span class="hl-comment">// Shared mutable state</span>
<span class="hl-keyword">let</span> <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-number">0</span>;

button.<span class="hl-fn">addEventListener</span>(<span class="hl-string">'click'</span>, () => {
  <span class="hl-comment">// ✅ No read yet — just queue</span>
  <span class="hl-fn">setTimeout</span>(() => {
    <span class="hl-comment">// ✅ Read + write both happen
    //    atomically inside callback</span>
    <span class="hl-var">count</span> = <span class="hl-good">count</span> + <span class="hl-number">1</span>;
    display.<span class="hl-var">textContent</span> = <span class="hl-var">count</span>;
  }, <span class="hl-number">50</span>);
});</pre>
        </div>

      </div>

      <p style="margin-top:16px">
        The key insight: in the buggy version the <strong>read</strong> of
        <code>count</code> happens <em>synchronously</em> at click time, so every
        rapid click captures the <em>same</em> stale value. In the fixed version the
        read is deferred <em>into</em> the callback, so by the time it executes,
        it sees the value that the previous callback already wrote.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Real-world patterns -->
    <div class="exp-card">
      <h3><span class="badge badge-fix">✅ Patterns</span> Real-World Solutions</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>1. Functional updater (React setState):</strong>
        <code>setCount(prev => prev + 1)</code> — React guarantees the callback
        receives the latest state, not a closure-captured snapshot.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>2. Queue / serialise:</strong> Use a Promise chain or an
        async queue so only one update runs at a time.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>3. Debounce / throttle:</strong> Collapse many rapid events
        into one, eliminating the race entirely.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>4. Immutable event sourcing:</strong> Never mutate shared state —
        append events to a log and derive current state by replaying them.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>5. Atomic operations:</strong> In environments with shared memory
        (SharedArrayBuffer + Web Workers), use <code>Atomics.add()</code> for
        true atomic read-modify-write.
      </p>
    </div>

