<div class="explainer">

  <!-- WHAT IS RECURSION DEPTH -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">📐</span> What Recursion Depth Actually Means</h2>
    <p>
      Every time a function calls itself, the JavaScript engine must <strong>suspend the current execution context</strong>
      and push a new <em>stack frame</em> onto the call stack. A stack frame holds everything needed to resume the
      caller later: local variables, the return address, the value of <code>this</code>, function arguments,
      and internal bookkeeping data. None of that can be discarded until the callee returns.
    </p>
    <p>
      For this fractal tree, each call to <code>drawBranch(depth)</code> spawns two child calls:
      <code>drawBranch(depth - 1)</code>. Those each spawn two more. The call stack therefore grows
      <strong>linearly with depth</strong> — at depth 12 the deepest chain is 12 frames tall — but the
      <strong>total number of calls grows as 2<sup>depth+1</sup> − 1</strong>. At depth 12 that is
      8,191 calls. This tree is well-behaved. Real-world unbounded recursion can be far worse.
    </p>

    <div class="stack-diagram">
      <div style="color:#8b949e;font-size:0.75rem;margin-bottom:8px;">CALL STACK — depth 4 example (rightmost branch path)</div>
      <div class="frame overflow"><span>drawBranch(0) ← leaf, returns immediately</span><span class="frame-label">TOP</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(1) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 3</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(2) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 2</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(3) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 1</span></div>
      <div class="frame active"><span>drawBranch(4) — waiting for child</span><span class="frame-label">depth 0</span></div>
      <div class="frame"><span>draw() — initial call</span><span class="frame-label">BOTTOM</span></div>
    </div>

    <p>
      Each frame above is <strong>alive and occupying memory simultaneously</strong>. The engine cannot garbage-collect
      any of them. They are all reachable, waiting. This is the fundamental cost of recursion: memory proportional to
      the maximum depth of the call chain, not just the number of operations.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- WHY STACK OVERFLOW -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">💥</span> Why Stack Overflows Happen — The Real Mechanics</h2>
    <p>
      JavaScript engines allocate a <strong>fixed-size contiguous memory region</strong> for the call stack.
      This is not the heap. It is a separate, much smaller region — typically between
      <em>500 KB and 2 MB</em> depending on the engine and platform. V8 (Node.js / Chrome) defaults to roughly
      <strong>984 frames</strong> in a typical configuration before throwing
      <code>RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded</code>.
      SpiderMonkey (Firefox) allows around 50,000 — it uses a different stack management strategy.
      JavaScriptCore (Safari) sits somewhere in between.
    </p>
    <p>
      The limit is not measured in frames directly. It is measured in <strong>bytes of stack space consumed</strong>.
      Each frame's size depends on how many local variables it has, the size of those variables, alignment padding,
      and the engine's internal overhead per frame. A function with 20 local <code>float64</code> values uses
      more stack per call than one with a single integer. This is why the exact frame limit varies between functions.
    </p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      ⚠️ <strong>The dangerous pattern:</strong> Recursion over user-supplied data with no depth guard.
      A JSON parser, a tree walker, a file-system traverser — any of these can receive input with
      arbitrarily deep nesting. If your recursion depth is bounded only by the input, a malicious or
      simply large input can crash your program with a stack overflow. This is not a theoretical concern.
      It is a real class of denial-of-service vulnerability.
    </div>

    <p>
      There is also a subtler failure mode: <strong>silent incorrect results</strong>. In some environments,
      stack overflows in worker threads or WebAssembly can produce undefined behavior rather than a clean
      exception. You cannot always rely on catching the error.
    </p>

    <pre><span class="cm">// This looks innocent. It is not.</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">sumArray</span>(<span class="param">arr</span>, <span class="param">index</span> = <span class="num">0</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (index >= arr.length) <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="num">0</span>;
  <span class="kw">return</span> arr[index] + <span class="fn">sumArray</span>(arr, index + <span class="num">1</span>); <span class="cm">// NOT tail position</span>
}

<span class="cm">// sumArray(new Array(100000)) → RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded
// The addition happens AFTER the recursive call returns.
// The frame cannot be reused. 100,000 frames pile up.</span></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- THE CODE -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">🌲</span> How This Tree Is Drawn</h2>
    <p>
      The fractal uses a classic recursive branch algorithm. Each call draws one line segment, then
      rotates the canvas context and calls itself twice with a reduced length and depth.
      The canvas transform stack mirrors the call stack — <code>save()</code> and <code>restore()</code>
      bracket each frame, which is why this approach is clean to write but still consumes stack frames.
    </p>
    <pre><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(<span class="param">ctx</span>, <span class="param">len</span>, <span class="param">depth</span>, <span class="param">maxDepth</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (depth === <span class="num">0</span>) <span class="kw">return</span>; <span class="cm">// base case — stop recursing</span>

  <span class="cm">// Hue shifts from brown (trunk) to green (leaves)</span>
  <span class="kw">const</span> t = depth / maxDepth;
  ctx.strokeStyle = <span class="fn">branchColor</span>(t);
  ctx.lineWidth = t * <span class="num">6</span> + <span class="num">0.5</span>;

  ctx.<span class="fn">beginPath</span>();
  ctx.<span class="fn">moveTo</span>(<span class="num">0</span>, <span class="num">0</span>);
  ctx.<span class="fn">lineTo</span>(<span class="num">0</span>, -len); <span class="cm">// draw upward in local space</span>
  ctx.<span class="fn">stroke</span>();

  ctx.<span class="fn">translate</span>(<span class="num">0</span>, -len); <span class="cm">// move to branch tip</span>

  <span class="cm">// Left child branch</span>
  ctx.<span class="fn">save</span>();
  ctx.<span class="fn">rotate</span>(-<span class="num">0.4</span>);
  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(ctx, len * <span class="num">0.72</span>, depth - <span class="num">1</span>, maxDepth);
  ctx.<span class="fn">restore</span>();

  <span class="cm">// Right child branch</span>
  ctx.<span class="fn">save</span>();
  ctx.<span class="fn">rotate</span>(<span class="num">0.4</span>);
  <span class="fn">drawBranch</span>(ctx, len * <span class="num">0.72</span>, depth - <span class="num">1</span>, maxDepth);
  ctx.<span class="fn">restore</span>();
}

<span class="cm">// Total calls = 2^(depth+1) - 1
// Max stack depth = depth + overhead frames
// This is safe up to depth ~12 because max stack depth is only 12 frames deep.</span></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- REAL SOLUTIONS -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">🔧</span> Real Solutions — Not Just "Add a Base Case"</h2>
    <p>
      Every tutorial tells you to add a base case. That is necessary but not sufficient. Here are the
      actual techniques engineers use in production systems:
    </p>

    <div class="solution-grid">
      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>1. Iterative with Explicit Stack</h3>
        <p>
          Replace the call stack with a heap-allocated array used as a stack. Push work items instead of
          calling recursively. The stack lives on the heap — it can grow to gigabytes. No stack overflow possible.
          This is the standard transformation for tree traversals.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>2. Tail Call Optimization</h3>
        <p>
          If the recursive call is the <em>very last operation</em> in the function (true tail position),
          the engine can reuse the current frame instead of pushing a new one. ES6 specifies TCO but only
          Safari implements it. In Node.js/V8 you cannot rely on it. Design for iterative anyway.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>3. Trampolining</h3>
        <p>
          Return a thunk (a zero-argument function) instead of calling recursively. A trampoline loop
          calls each thunk in a flat while loop. Stack depth stays at 1. Works in any language.
          Useful when you cannot restructure the algorithm into explicit iteration easily.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>4. Memoization + Depth Guard</h3>
        <p>
          Cache results to avoid redundant calls (critical for overlapping subproblems like Fibonacci),
          and add an explicit maximum depth parameter that throws a descriptive error rather than
          silently overflowing. Always fail loudly with context.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>5. Continuation-Passing Style</h3>
        <p>
          Thread an explicit continuation callback through each call. The actual work is deferred and
          can be scheduled across event loop ticks with <code>setTimeout(fn, 0)</code> or
          <code>queueMicrotask()</code>, preventing stack buildup for large async workloads.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="solution-card">
        <h3>6. Increase Stack Size (Runtime)</h3>
        <p>
          In Node.js: <code>node --stack-size=65536 app.js</code> sets the stack to 64 MB.
          This is a last resort and a band-aid. It raises the ceiling without fixing the underlying
          unbounded growth. Use only when you control the input size absolutely.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p style="margin-top:16px;">
      Below is the iterative stack transformation of a recursive tree traversal — the most broadly applicable fix:
    </p>

    <pre><span class="cm">// RECURSIVE — breaks at depth ~984 in V8</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">walkTree</span>(<span class="param">node</span>) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (!node) <span class="kw">return</span>;
  <span class="fn">process</span>(node);
  <span class="fn">walkTree</span>(node.left);  <span class="cm">// pushes a frame</span>
  <span class="fn">walkTree</span>(node.right); <span class="cm">// pushes a frame</span>
}

<span class="cm">// ITERATIVE — never overflows, heap is the only limit</span>
<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">walkTreeIterative</span>(<span class="param">root</span>) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> stack = [root]; <span class="cm">// explicit stack on the heap</span>
  <span class="kw">while</span> (stack.length > <span class="num">0</span>) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> node = stack.<span class="fn">pop</span>();
    <span class="kw">if</span> (!node) <span class="kw">continue</span>;
    <span class="fn">process</span>(node);
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>(node.right); <span class="cm">// push right first so left is processed first</span>
    stack.<span class="fn">push</span>(node.left);
  }
}

<span class="cm">// TRAMPOLINE — recursive logic, iterative execution</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">trampoline</span> = <span class="param">fn</span> => (...<span class="param">args</span>) => {
  <span class="kw">let</span> result = <span class="fn">fn</span>(...args);
  <span class="kw">while</span> (<span class="kw">typeof</span> result === <span class="str">'function'</span>) result = <span class="fn">result</span>();
  <span class="kw">return</span> result;
};

<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="fn">factorial</span> = <span class="fn">trampoline</span>(
  <span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">fact</span>(<span class="param">n</span>, <span class="param">acc</span> = <span class="num">1</span>) {
    <span class="kw">if</span> (n <= <span class="num">1</span>) <span class="kw">return</span> acc;
    <span class="kw">return</span> () => <span class="fn">fact</span>(n - <span class="num">1</span>, n * acc); <span class="cm">// return thunk, not recursive call</span>
  }
);
<span class="fn">factorial</span>(<span class="num">100000</span>); <span class="cm">// works fine — stack depth never exceeds 2</span></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- WHEN IS RECURSION FINE -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2><span class="icon">✅</span> When Recursion Is Perfectly Fine</h2>
    <p>
      Recursion is not inherently bad. It is the right tool when:
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="tag">Safe</span> <strong>Maximum depth is bounded by structure, not input size.</strong>
      A balanced binary search tree of one million nodes has a depth of only 20. Recursing over it is fine.
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="tag">Safe</span> <strong>You own the input and can validate depth before recursing.</strong>
      This fractal tree is capped at 12. Twelve frames is nothing. The code is cleaner recursive than iterative.
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="tag green">Ideal</span> <strong>The problem is naturally self-similar.</strong>
      Fractals, parsers for nested grammars, divide-and-conquer algorithms (merge sort, quicksort) —
      these express their structure most clearly as recursion. Forcing them iterative often produces
      harder-to-maintain code with no real benefit.
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="tag orange">Caution</span> <strong>Depth depends on user/network input.</strong>
      Always add an explicit depth guard with a meaningful error message. Never let the runtime decide
      when to crash.
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="tag red">Danger</span> <strong>Mutual recursion over unbounded data.</strong>
      Function A calls B which calls A. Each hop uses a frame. Mutual recursion is harder to reason about,
      harder to convert to iteration, and harder to tail-call optimize. Restructure if possible.
    </p>
  </div>

</div>

<script>
const canvas = document.getElementById('tree');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
const slider = document.getElementById('depthSlider');
const depthVal = document.getElementById('depthVal');
const statBranches = document.getElementById('statBranches');
const statCalls = document.getElementById('statCalls');
const statFrames = document.getElementById('statFrames');
const statMemory = document.getElementById('statMemory');

function branchColor(t) {
  // t=1 is trunk (brown), t=0 is leaf (bright green)
  const r = Math.round(101 + (34 - 101) * (1 - t));
  const g = Math.round(67 + (197 - 67) * (1 - t));
  const b = Math.round(33 + (94 - 33) * (1 - t));
  return `rgb(${r},${g},${b})`;
}

function leafGlow(ctx, x, y, depth) {
  const grd = ctx.createRadialGradient(x, y, 0, x, y, 6);
  grd.addColorStop(0, 'rgba(100,230,120,0.7)');
  grd.addColorStop(1, 'rgba(100,230,120,0)');
  ctx.fillStyle = grd;
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.arc(x, y, 5, 0, Math.PI * 2);
  ctx.fill();
}

function drawBranch(ctx, len, depth, maxDepth) {
  if (depth === 0) {
    // Draw leaf glow at current position
    leafGlow(ctx, 0, 0, depth);
    return;
  }

  const t = depth / maxDepth;
  ctx.strokeStyle = branchColor(t);
  ctx.lineWidth = Math.max(t * 7 + 0.3, 0.5);
  ctx.lineCap = 'round';

  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.moveTo(0, 0);
  ctx.lineTo(0, -len);
  ctx.stroke();

  ctx.translate(0, -len);

  // Slight asymmetry makes the tree look natural
  const angleLeft = 0.38 + 0.04 * (1 - t);
  const angleRight = 0.42 + 0.03 * (1 - t);
  const ratio = 0.68 + 0.06 * (1 - t);

  ctx.save();
  ctx.rotate(-angleLeft);
  drawBranch(ctx, len * ratio, depth - 1, maxDepth);
  ctx.restore();

  ctx.save();
  ctx.rotate(angleRight);
  drawBranch(ctx, len * (ratio - 0.02), depth - 1, maxDepth);
  ctx.restore();
}

function draw(depth) {
  const W = canvas.width;
  const H = canvas.height;
  ctx.clearRect(0, 0, W, H);

  // Background gradient
  const bg = ctx.createLinearGradient(0, 0, 0, H);
  bg.addColorStop(0, '#0a0f1a');
  bg.addColorStop(1, '#0d1a0a');
  ctx.fillStyle = bg;
  ctx.fillRect(0, 0, W, H);

  // Ground line
  ctx.strokeStyle = '#2a3a2a';
  ctx.lineWidth = 1;
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.moveTo(0, H - 30);
  ctx.lineTo(W, H - 30);
  ctx.stroke();

  const trunkLen = Math.min(H * 0.22, 90);

  ctx.save();
  ctx.translate(W / 2, H - 30);
  drawBranch(ctx, trunkLen, depth, depth);
  ctx.restore();
}

function updateStats(depth) {
  // Total calls = 2^(depth+1) - 1
  const calls = Math.pow(2, depth + 1) - 1;
  // Total segments = calls - leaves = 2^depth - 1 internal + 2^depth leaves = calls
  // Branches (line segments drawn) = 2^(depth+1) - 1 - 2^depth = 2^depth - 1
  const branches = Math.pow(2, depth) - 1 + Math.pow(2, depth); // internal + leaves
  const maxStack = depth + 3; // function frames + draw + global
  // Rough frame size: ~200 bytes for this function (args, locals, return addr, ctx ptr)
  const frameBytes = 200;
  const totalStack = maxStack * frameBytes;
  const kb = (totalStack / 1024).toFixed(1);

  statBranches.textContent = branches.toLocaleString();
  statCalls.textContent = calls.toLocaleString();
  statFrames.textContent = maxStack;
  statMemory.textContent = kb + ' KB';
}

function redraw() {
  const depth = parseInt(slider.value, 10);
  depthVal.textContent = depth;
  draw(depth);
  updateStats(depth);
}

slider.addEventListener('input', redraw);
redraw();
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

