            <h3>🐛 Why the Buggy Version Fails</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom:8px;">
                Each task reads the <em>current</em> value of <code>sharedProgress</code>,
                adds its chunk, then writes back. But because JavaScript's event loop
                interleaves microtasks and macrotasks, multiple tasks can read the
                <strong>same stale value</strong> before any of them write back:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Task A reads <code>progress = 20</code></li>
                <li>Task B reads <code>progress = 20</code> (same snapshot!)</li>
                <li>Task A writes <code>progress = 30</code></li>
                <li>Task B writes <code>progress = 30</code> — <strong>Task A's update is lost!</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:8px;">
                Result: the final value is <strong>wrong</strong>, updates are skipped,
                and in some runs the bar can even <strong>exceed 100%</strong>.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="explain-block fix-explain">
            <h3>✅ How the Fixed Version Works</h3>
            <p style="margin-bottom:8px;">
                The fix uses a <strong>Promise-based serial queue</strong> (mutex pattern).
                Each task must acquire a lock before touching the shared variable.
                If the lock is held, the task waits until it's released:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Only <strong>one task at a time</strong> can read-modify-write</li>
                <li>Other tasks <strong>queue up</strong> and wait their turn</li>
                <li>No stale reads — every task sees the latest committed value</li>
                <li>Final result is always exactly <strong>100%</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top:8px;">
                This is equivalent to a <strong>mutex / critical section</strong>
                in multi-threaded languages like Java or C++, adapted for JS's
                async/await model using a chained Promise queue.
