<!-- ══════════════════ EXPLANATION ══════════════════ -->
<div class="explanation">
  <h2>🔍 What's actually happening and why it matters</h2>

  <p>
    JavaScript is <span class="hl">single-threaded</span>, but <code>setTimeout</code> callbacks are
    scheduled asynchronously. When multiple callbacks fire in rapid succession they all read the
    <span class="hl-red">same stale snapshot</span> of shared state before any of them has had a
    chance to write their update back — a classic
    <span class="hl">read-modify-write race condition</span>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span class="hl-red">Buggy pattern:</span> a single <code>completedTasks</code> counter is
    incremented by every callback. Because JS is cooperative (not preemptive), the race doesn't
    corrupt a single increment — but the <span class="hl-red">overall percentage is recomputed
    from a shared total</span> that tasks overwrite without coordination. The real-world version of
    this bug shows up when you add debouncing, batching, or network calls: two responses arrive,
    both read <code>total = 3</code>, both write <code>total = 4</code>, and you silently lose one
    unit of work. The bar jumps, stalls, or never reaches 100%.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span class="hl-grn">Fixed pattern:</span> each task owns <span class="hl">its own isolated
    progress slot</span> in an array. The overall percentage is derived by
    <span class="hl">reducing the array</span> — a pure read with no shared write target. No task
    can corrupt another task's slot. The aggregate is always computed fresh from the ground truth,
    so the bar is always consistent regardless of scheduling order.
  </p>

  <div class="steps">
    <div class="step">
      <strong>🐛 Bug Step 1</strong>
      Tasks A, B, C all start. Each reads <code>completedTasks = 0</code>.
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <strong>🐛 Bug Step 2</strong>
      Task A finishes, writes <code>completedTasks = 1</code>. Bar → 33%.
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <strong>🐛 Bug Step 3</strong>
      Tasks B &amp; C finish almost simultaneously. Both read stale value,
      both write <code>completedTasks = 2</code>. Bar → 67% — one task lost!
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <strong>✅ Fix</strong>
      Each task writes only to <code>progress[i]</code>. Overall = <code>sum(progress) / total</code>.
      No shared write target. Always correct.
    </div>
  </div>
