  <p>
    <span class="tag tag-bug">BUG</span>&nbsp;
    The bug is <strong>not</strong> in the Canvas API. The Canvas
    <code>arc()</code> method works perfectly. The bug lives entirely in the
    <strong>Fibonacci sequence generator</strong>: the second base case was set
    to <code>fib(1) = 0</code> instead of <code>fib(1) = 1</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span class="tag tag-info">WHY IT MATTERS</span>&nbsp;
    Each quarter-circle arc in a Fibonacci spiral has a radius equal to the
    n-th Fibonacci number (scaled to pixels). When <code>fib(1) = 0</code>,
    the sequence starts <code>0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 3…</code> instead of
    <code>0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13…</code>. The first several arcs are drawn
    with radius 0 (invisible dots), and subsequent arcs are offset in position
    because the cumulative bounding-box math is wrong — making it look like
    the spiral "jumps" or overlaps randomly.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span class="tag tag-fix">FIX</span>&nbsp;
    Change the seed from <code>let a = 0, b = 0</code> to
    <code>let a = 0, b = 1</code>. Everything else — the canvas arc calls,
    the rotation logic, the colour scheme — was correct all along.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span class="tag tag-info">LESSON</span>&nbsp;
    Before blaming a browser API, always verify your input data. A spiral that
    "looks wrong" is almost always caused by wrong radii, wrong pivot points,
    or wrong angles — all of which come from application logic, not from
    <code>CanvasRenderingContext2D</code>.
  </p>
