<!-- ============================================================ EXPLANATION -->
<div class="explanation">
  <h3>🔬 What's Actually Happening — The Bugs Explained</h3>

  <h4>The Setup</h4>
  <p>
    Five async "tasks" simulate work by firing progress updates via <code>setTimeout</code>.
    Each task has a random duration and tick rate. They all run concurrently.
    The goal: a master progress bar showing overall completion (0–100%).
  </p>

  <h4>Bug #1 — Read-Modify-Write Race (the classic)</h4>
  <p>
    The buggy version stores a single shared <code>sharedProgress</code> number.
    Every task callback does:
  </p>
  <pre>
<span class="c">// Task A fires. Reads stale value, adds its delta, writes back.</span>
<span class="bad">sharedProgress += myDelta;</span>   <span class="c">// Task B may have ALSO read the old value</span>
<span class="bad">updateBar(sharedProgress);</span>   <span class="c">// one write silently stomps the other</span>
  </pre>
  <p>
    In a single-threaded JS engine this still causes logical races because
    <code>setTimeout</code> callbacks interleave. Task B reads <code>sharedProgress = 40</code>,
    Task A also reads <code>40</code>, both add their delta, both write — one update is
    <strong>silently lost</strong>. The bar jumps backward or stalls.
  </p>

  <h4>Bug #2 — Stale Closure Capture</h4>
  <pre>
<span class="kw">let</span> taskProgress = <span class="num">0</span>;          <span class="c">// captured by closure at schedule time</span>
<span class="fn">setTimeout</span>(<span class="kw">function</span> tick() {
  taskProgress += increment;   <span class="c">// fine locally...</span>
  <span class="bad">sharedProgress += increment;</span> <span class="c">// but sharedProgress was already mutated</span>
                               <span class="c">// by OTHER tasks between ticks — stale!</span>
  <span class="fn">setTimeout</span>(tick, delay);
}, delay);
  </pre>

  <h4>Bug #3 — No Completion Guard (phantom updates)</h4>
  <pre>
<span class="c">// Task finishes at 100% but its setTimeout chain keeps firing</span>
<span class="bad">if (taskProgress &gt;= 100) return;</span>  <span class="c">// too late — already scheduled next tick</span>
<span class="bad">sharedProgress += delta;</span>           <span class="c">// pushes master bar PAST 100%</span>
  </pre>
  <p>The master bar can exceed 100% or oscillate near the end.</p>

  <h4>The Fix — Derived State, No Shared Mutation</h4>
  <pre>
<span class="c">// Each task owns ONLY its own slice. Never touches shared state.</span>
<span class="good">taskState[id].progress = clamp(newVal, 0, 100);</span>

<span class="c">// Master recomputes from source of truth on every tick.</span>
<span class="good">function getMasterProgress() {</span>
  <span class="kw">const</span> total = taskState.<span class="fn">reduce</span>((sum, t) =&gt; sum + t.progress, <span class="num">0</span>);
  <span class="kw">return</span> total / taskState.length;   <span class="c">// pure derivation, no mutation</span>
<span class="good">}</span>
  </pre>
  <ul class="bug-list">
    <li><span class="bad">BUGGY:</span> shared mutable accumulator — multiple writers, no lock</li>
    <li><span class="good">FIXED:</span> each task writes only its own isolated slot</li>
    <li><span class="bad">BUGGY:</span> master progress is <em>state</em> — can be corrupted</li>
    <li><span class="good">FIXED:</span> master progress is <em>derived</em> — always consistent</li>
    <li><span class="bad">BUGGY:</span> no cancellation — phantom ticks after completion</li>
    <li><span class="good">FIXED:</span> each task tracks its own timer ID and clears it</li>
    <li><span class="bad">BUGGY:</span> delta accumulation drifts — tasks double-count increments</li>
    <li><span class="good">FIXED:</span> absolute values only — <code>progress = newAbsoluteValue</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h4>Why This Kills Production Systems</h4>
  <p>
    Replace "progress bar" with "order quantity", "account balance", "retry counter",
    or "connection pool size". The same read-modify-write race on shared mutable state
    causes inventory overselling, double charges, infinite retry storms, and pool exhaustion.
    The fix is always the same: <strong>isolate writes, derive reads.</strong>
  </p>
