<div class="explanation">
  <h2>⚠️ Why blaming the GC is wrong</h2>
  <p>
    JavaScript uses <strong>mark-and-sweep garbage collection</strong>. The GC can only free objects that have
    <strong>zero reachable references</strong>. When you remove a widget from the DOM but forget to call
    <code>removeEventListener</code>, the listener callback holds a <strong>closure reference</strong> back to the
    widget object. The GC sees that reference and correctly keeps the object alive — it is not a bug in the GC,
    it is a bug in <em>your</em> code.
  </p>
  <p>
    Every "removed" widget in the buggy version still has: (1) an active <strong>setInterval</strong> timer ticking
    in the background, (2) a <strong>mousemove</strong> listener on <code>document</code> capturing the widget
    object in its closure, and (3) a <strong>resize</strong> listener on <code>window</code>. These three roots
    keep the entire widget object — and its DOM subtree reference — <strong>permanently reachable</strong>. The
    GC never collects them because it should not.
  </p>
  <p>
