<div class="explanation">
  <h2>🔬 Why This Happens — No Hedging</h2>
  <p>
    IEEE 754 double-precision floating point represents numbers in binary. The decimal value
    <code>0.1</code> <strong class="highlight-red">cannot be represented exactly in binary</strong>
    — just like <code>1/3</code> cannot be written exactly in decimal. It becomes an infinitely
    repeating binary fraction that gets truncated at 52 mantissa bits. So <code>0.1</code> stored
    in a float is actually <code>0.1000000000000000055511151231257827021181583404541015625</code>.
  </p>
  <p>
    When you add <code>$4.99 + $3.99</code> in floating point, you are not adding those numbers.
    You are adding their binary approximations. The rounding errors accumulate and the result is
    <code class="highlight-red">8.879999999999999</code> — not <code>8.88</code>. Triple-equals
    then compares this garbage value against <code>8.88</code> and correctly reports
    <strong class="highlight-red">false</strong> — which is the wrong answer for your business logic.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong class="highlight-green">The fix is non-negotiable:</strong> store all monetary values
    as integer cents. <code>$4.99</code> becomes <code>499</code>. Addition of integers is exact.
    <code>499 + 399 === 898</code> is always <code>true</code>. Divide by 100 only at the
    <em>last moment</em> for display using <code>.toFixed(2)</code>. Never use floats as the
    source of truth for money. Every major payment processor, accounting system, and financial
    standard works in integer minor units for exactly this reason.
  </p>
