<body>

<h1>🔥 Widget Dashboard Memory Leak Demo</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Proving that "the GC will handle it" is dangerously wrong</p>

<!-- ── GC Myth Buster ── -->
<div class="myth-banner">
    <h2>⚠️ The Incompetent Diagnosis: "It's a Garbage Collector Issue"</h2>
    <div class="myth-vs-fact">
        <div class="myth-box">
            <h3>❌ WRONG — What the fool said</h3>
            <p>
                "The garbage collector will clean up those deleted widgets automatically.
                JavaScript GC handles all memory, so you don't need to manually remove
                event listeners or DOM references. Just delete the element and GC takes care of it."
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact-box">
            <h3>✅ CORRECT — What's actually happening</h3>
            <p>
                The GC <em>cannot</em> collect objects that are still reachable.
                Event listeners registered on external targets (window, document, other elements)
                and references stored in closures or arrays keep the widget objects in a
                <strong>reachability chain</strong>. The GC sees them as live. This is not a
                GC bug — it is a <strong>programmer-created reference leak</strong>.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ── Why GC Can't Save You ── -->
<div class="explanation">
    <h2>🧠 Why the GC Diagnosis Is Categorically Wrong</h2>
    <p>
        The JavaScript garbage collector uses <strong>mark-and-sweep</strong> reachability analysis.
        An object is collected <em>only</em> when <strong>zero live references</strong> point to it.
        The problem here is never the GC — the GC works perfectly. The problem is that
        <strong>the developer created references that were never cleaned up</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>The three specific leaks in the broken panel below:</p>
    <ul class="reason-list">
        <li>
            <strong>Orphaned event listeners:</strong> Each widget registers a <code>mousemove</code>
            listener on <code>window</code>. The <code>window</code> object is a GC root — it is
            <em>always</em> reachable. Its listener list holds a closure that captures the widget
            object. Even after the DOM element is removed, the GC traces: window → listener →
            closure → widget object. The widget <strong>cannot be collected</strong>.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Global reference array:</strong> Each widget is pushed into
            <code>leakedWidgetRegistry</code>. That array is never cleaned. The GC traces:
            global scope → registry array → widget object. Still reachable. Still alive.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Detached DOM with retained reference:</strong> The widget's DOM node is
            removed from the document but the JS object still holds a <code>.element</code>
            property pointing to it. The detached subtree stays in memory because the JS object
            is still alive (for the two reasons above), and the JS object stays alive because
            the DOM node reference creates a cycle that the GC actually <em>does</em> handle —
            but it never gets the chance because the outer references prevent collection entirely.
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        <strong>The fix has nothing to do with the GC.</strong> You must explicitly call
        <code>removeEventListener</code> with the same function reference, nullify stored
        references, and remove entries from registries — <em>before</em> discarding the widget.
    </p>
</div>

